<br>
Indian Nuclear Power Programme Reaches New Milestone <br>
The start of civil construction work at India’s first commercial-scale fast reactor represents a major step forward for the Indian nuclear power development programme – and a technological milestone for nuclear power world-wide.<br>
<br>
 <br>
Indian nuclear officials say the start-up of the 500-megawatt prototype fast breeder reactor (PFBR) will create a springboard for the use of India’s considerable thorium resources as the basis of a completely new commercial nuclear fuel cycle. <br>
It will also make India only the second country in the world to have an operational commercial-scale fast breeder reactor. France’s Superphénix was closed down for political and economic reasons in 1998, and the only such reactor currently in operation is Russia’s BN-600 at Beloyarsk, which has operated successfully since 1981. <br>
